comments.text:
Glad you liked the print :)
The tolerances needed for a proper snap are very tight, actually tighter than the printer-to-printer variations. The width of the plastic string laid down varies, thus the diameter of the studs varies. (Impacted by nozzle diameter, layer height, extruder speed, nozzle temperature, material, filament humidity, etc ...)
The open studs can flex a bit more, so should be easier to get 'snappy'. Playing a bit with the printer settings or tweaking the design file may well get you a proper snappy little boat :-)

description.text:
Printable replacement keyring and keytops for a Corona portable typewriter of the thirties to late forties. In case the original keys are damaged or missing, new keytops and plastic locking rings to fit onto the stems. Replacement for the metal-rimmed dimpled keytops. 
Keytops have the hollowed top surface and need a printed sticker to be applied for the lettering for the machine's layout. The tops snap into the keyrings. The keyrings snap onto the metal pads at the end of the keybars of the typewriter.
Because of some variations in exact diameter of the metal pads of the stems and in printing accuracy, you may want to add a small pad of double-sided adhesive tape to prevent rotation and keep the ring in place. Ideally the ring snaps over the pad and locks with the key stem cutting into the flags at the back of the pad. 
The Key~ parts fit the 14mm keys and the Shift~ parts fit the 16mm shift keys.

Cleaning parts With FDM printing, sand down or cut off any stringing or final drip of the printer for correct fit. Use one or two layers of printed label on the keytops for a smooth and comfortable keytop.

description.text: Info on the tags here: http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/ee804885%28v=surface.10%29.aspx Parametric surface tag generation. The tags need to be 3/4" square, but you can set the byte number, border, back, corners, etc. Tested working on the 1.0 version of the surface. If they're not recognized as tags, take a surface picture - you need to get the dot/non-dot contrast to be pretty high. These need to be printed in UV-reflective filament - the clear doesn't work. Also, the height makes a big difference - if they're too short you get too much background reflection from inside the tag. I colored the insides in with black marker.

The tags are 3/4" square, borders are optional.  Add to a thing, and now you have a cool printed surface control.

description.text: I've been making action figures lately (see http://tekeian.posterous.com/pages/action-figures). Here is a version for Thingiverse. I've printed 80 action figures of various designs. One of the goals is a quick finish and assembly time. Only a flat file and an X-Acto knife are needed for raft trimming, then glue it up. The arms can be articulated by gluing some filament to each arm and running them through the hole in the body. The hands (or claws) can hold objects with a ~3mm edge.

Except for the helmet and lightning bolts, all the parts are printed with a raft. The robot body, seen in the parts image, has already been trimmed. The legs can be printed without a raft, but, the permitter of the foot may come out ragged. If you use the HBP, I suspect you can print the limbs without a raft.
I used a ToM with ABP and Print-o-matic turned on in RepG. Every few action figures, I lightly sand the belt. The rafts are essential once your ABP belt starts to curl at the edges.

description.text:
description from Chuck314159:
This is a low profile conversion kit for the ZMR250 V2. It includes a 28x28 camera mount on two screws to allow adjustable tilt. I am using a sony mini HAD which fits perfectly! The skirt is designed for use with 3mm thick arms. I use it with two carbon bottom plates and 30mm M3 bolts and it is really strong. ZMR_LowRacer_V2_3mm_vented_left_XT60.stl:
this version is modified to fit XT60, and is vented: it comes at 37g. ZMR_LowRacer_V2_4mm vented left XT60.stl:
same as above for 4mm arms ZMR_LowRacer_V2_3mm vented left XT60-middle arm.stl:
this version has middle arms to use spacers as dampers, and lower the CoG.
(this version might need to thicken a bit the spacer around the arm when done in flexi PLA: I will update if needed) ZMR_LowRacer_V2_3mm vented left XT60-middle 3MM arm separated.stl:
same as above with detached bottom spacer to ease access to camera. ZMR_LowRacer_V2_3mm vented left XT60-middle 3MM arm separated - 32x32 cam.stl:
same as above for bigger cameras.
enjoy ;) PS: I plan on adding USB hole on the side, lower hight to 14mm, and modify arm spacer to get material on both side of the arm to use spacers as damper when thing made with Flexi PLA.

title: Pedal insert LED lights for Gotway unicycle

description.text:
This is a case to accomodate one battery, 3 leds and a mercury switch. Its size allows it to be inserted within a Gotway MCM2 and MCM3 ( but not MSuper or MCM4 ) unicycle pedal and provide a way to be seen by other people while riding your wheel (See video and picture). Depending on the leds used, you will obtain various effects.
Here is a video showing two options:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GVOQImmvStY&feature=youtu.be
They automatically switch on when you unfold the pedal:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zSM35KjcctA Here are parts that you will need. Mercury switch: http://www.ebay.com/itm/141807317185
Batteries and charger: http://www.ebay.com/itm/181725362921
Prototype PCB: http://www.ebay.com/itm/400985368376
Battery spring plate sets : http://www.ebay.com/itm/231239955456
Leds: http://www.ebay.com/itm/400985246280 You just solder 3 leds on a piece of PCB, parallel wiring (not serial), wire to the battery spring plates with the mercury switch in between, stuff the whole thing inside the case, and give the mercury switch the right angle to turn the power on when the pedal is down (tricky, use tweezers) and you are done.
Here is a video showing the mercury switch in action:
https://youtu.be/gQ4Imk2E2i0 Just add a bit of soft foam on one side of the case so that it stays in place once inside the pedal. I was asked to post this by someone at the world's biggest Electrical Unicycle gathering in Paris last week end (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Hdt5KFjgPQI) I recommand using multi colored leds, that can sustain the 3.7 to 4.2Volts of the battery with no damage.
Some Leds will die with only 2V so check them before. Diodes can be added to lower the voltage independantly from the current.

I needed a new profile image. While I'm proud of the project that lead to my former "TV face" image, it didn't really say "Thingiverse" Having just successfully created a 3 color bottle opener, I knew the time for a multi-color portrait had come. This is my first attempt at mashing colors together on the same layer like this. I'm really happy with the results. Hopefully others will take this technique and run with it. Turns out you don't need dual extruders to make a multi-colored part! tv-face: http://brettbeauregard.com/blog/tag/hdtv-mount/
3 color opener: http://brettbeauregard.com/blog/2011/09/three-color-3d-print/

This was a fairly involved process, so I'll break it into "Image Processing", "Printing", and "Finishing" Image processing

  • There's probably a really easy way to turn an image into 4 colors using GIMP, but I couldn't find it. So I used http://obamicon.me instead. Kind of cheesy, but exactly what I needed

  • Using Inkscape, I turned the image into 4 separate color paths using the trace bitmap tool (Scans=4, stack scans = false)

  • The trace tool creates splines, which are incompatible with the next step. To get rid of them I modified each color path in turn, selecting all the nodes at once then clicking "make selected segments lines".

  • I then saved each color path into a separate DXF.

  • Using OpenSCAD I was able to extrude each color to the thickness of one Z layer (0.36mm in my case) and put them into separate STLs. I wanted to print these on a base for easy removal, so for my base color (white) I created a rectangle 2 z-layers thick, then put the white extruded path on top of that. The other colors started at Z=0;
    • Printing

  • The first color was printed as normal.

  • I then edited the Z-offet in the motherboard settings to be 2 layers higher (smaller) than before (0.72mm in my case)

  • When Skeining the remaining colors, I unchecked "Activate outline" on the outline tab.

  • The remaining 3 colors where then printed one at a time at the modified Z-offset, without outline being activated.
    • Finishing
    If you look at the closeup you can see that I put WAY too much plastic down during this print. A little sandpaper made the image much crisper. in the future I'll need to play around to find the Skeinforge settings that work best. Also, by printing black last I left myself with a little streak as the extruder nozzle left at the end of the the print. An X-acto knife took that right off.

Print one of each of these.  You should be able to print them on the stock Printrbot Simple build plate if you rotate them 45 degrees and bring the slic3r skirt in to 1mm from the part (and possibly fudge the numbers for how large of an area you can print on).  They are almost mirror images of each other except that one hole shifts slightly to match the way the original X carriage tries to compensate for the different positions of the fishing line.  
You may need to ream out the holes in which the rods should fit.  I typically do this by hand with a 5/16" drill bit, because using a powered drill has blown right through the cap for me a number of times.  
Removing the old build plate is rather easily done, and only costs you two zip ties each time you have to do so.  The hardware can then be reused to mount a new, larger build plate.  
The interior holes at the negative-Y side of the brackets can be used to balance out the force caused by tightening the fishing line, but I found that it wasn't strictly necessary.  
You might want to increase the infill (I used 0.3 and it may have been too little) and possibly change the angle, since you'll likely need to rotate the part 45 degrees (which matched my infill angle and possibly weakened the part).  My first attempt is starting the split where the fishing line is mounted and I think it is due to these factors.

title: Fitbit Zip box for dog collar (another one)

description.text:
Box for fitbit zip to mount on a dog collar.
The slot for the collar is 27x3mm. The collars my dogs have are approx 25x2.5mm. The fitbit zip fits in VERY tight - not that it feels like it is breaking or anything, but I will not fall out by accident, even if you take the box of the collar.
Since the fitbit zip is shaped slightly like an isosceles trapezium, the fitbit zip will only fit into the hole in one way. There is nothing on the box to tell you how that is, but it should be kind of obvious once you have both in your hand.

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Notes: I printed this standing as the preview/render shows here. I have a theory that a print is stronger in the X/Y dirrection that in the Z, since X/Y is extruded in one flow, where as Z added layer after layer. Therefore at very best a print will be almost as strong in Z as in the X/Y plane, but Z will never be stronger that X/Y... By printing this standing, the clamps that holds onto the collar will be as strong as possible (according to above theory), because they are printed in the X/Y plane. The entire box will then be orientated in the dirrection that causes it to be weakest, but since it it so much thicker than the clamps, it is much less a problem.

One of the first designs i liked on thingiverse, was this box by Klodeko http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:290281. Now I finally got fitbit zips for my dogs, and I wanted to print it. However, it turned out that it was not manifold and my slicer could not cope with it, and hence I could not print it. I have talked to Klodeko previously, and being a very kind person, I'm sure he/she would have fixed it and uploaded a new version. But I also needed these mounts for christmas presents, so I thought it was quicker/safer to remake the already brilliant design. I will not try to take any credit from Klodeko for this design.

title: Prusa I3 Acrylic Frame Filament Holder

description.text:
Looked at other filament holders on Thingiverse and found most of them to be mounted on the side of the frame or off center at the top. None of the options at the time appeared to work for me so I decided to create my own.   I wanted the least amount of drag on the motor and the weight of the filament to be balanced directly above the frame as it is acrylic.  I would expect that over time that it might warp or shift if mounted off center with the weight being unevenly distributed.    
Just note the inside width of the filament holder that rests directly on frame was designed with a slightly larger opening intentionally.  I cut an inserted a small piece of foam to prevent any vibration that might occur with plastic resting directly on plastic.  The foam dampens the vibration that might be transferred when spool is rotating.   
I've also attached two different filament holder inserts as the inner diameter was not the same between them.  One insert is for filament from "justpla" with an inner diameter of around 31mm and the other for filament from "Foldger Tech" which has an inner diameter of near 57mm.
The filament holder tabs file is an addition to the filament holder.  This will help stabilize the holder and prevent prevent any tilting from left to right.  The rod that runs through the filament holder is just a wooden dowel I found in my garage which has a diameter of 21mm. I chose this rod just for its convenience.  You might be also be able to find something laying around that works for you.

Prusa I3

Notes: Be aware that the inside width of filament holder is slightly wider than acrylic frame intentionally. So don't be surprised if when printed there is excess play front to back. Cut and stick a piece of foam pad and insert. This will cut down on any vibration that might occur.

title: Stepper motor to 20mm wire chain adapter

description.text: Clamps around a stepper motor and provides an end to a 20mm wire chain.

More or less an exact copy of http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:34048 only it's in openscad and is parametric (and slices properly for me). It also terminates the opposite side of the wire chain so you can use it with http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:57533 on your prusa I3 with a greg (wade) extruder. You can print it on its side if you use support, otherwise print it vertically (check the scad), but beware the large bridge at the top. I'd recommend making the motor_width variable slightly smaller than your motor's actual width so it fits tight (otherwise it slides too easily). The STL I included uses 42mm for the motor_width whereas my steppers are NEMA 17 (44mm). It's also compiled with trace_width = 0.66 and layer_height = 0.3 (2.2 WOT). If you want to compile it yourself, you'll also need one of the files from the 20mm chain (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:10946) in the same folder as this scad.

It's almost Christmas, so bring out the Snow Globes! This one combines MakerBot 3D Printing with littleBits Electronics. It's a long but rewarding project! The electronics are really simple to work with and are housed in the base of the globe. Give us a shout if you run into any issues! Video Link: https://youtu.be/yIq1SI4NSpM Details of any non-3D Printed parts that are required are listed at the bottom of the page.

Notes: All parts print without Support. Support has been modelled into the 'Holly' parts - these can be broken off post-printing. Both the Lower and Upper Bases have been modelled with corner tabs to help with adhesion and avoid warping on the Z18 build plate. These can be snapped off post-printing.

Step 1: Lower and Upper Bases The Lower and Upper Bases have been designed with corner tabs to help with adhesion and avoid warping on the Z18 build plate. These tabs can be snapped off using a pair of pliers. You may need to sand the edges down for a smoother finish. Step 2: Holly The Holly Leaves have been modelled with built in Support. This can be removed easily with a pair of pliers. You may need to clear away any excess filament with a file or craft knife. Step 3: Assembly Start by snapping the roofs onto the house. It should be a fairly snug fit, but don't worry if its a little loose, you can always add some adhesive to keep them in place. Slide the yellow Door Front piece into the underside of the house, so that it is flat against the front door. There is an undercut gap in the house for this piece to slide into. This translucent yellow will give the whole house a warm glow when the LED shines through it! Place the two larger trees in the larger holes in the Upper Base, and the smaller trees next to each other in the smaller holes. We used some adhesive to secure them in place. Snap the Lake into place, and slide the Pier into the slot sitting just above the Lake, cut out of the Upper Base. Snap the MBT Logo into the front of the Upper Base, marked out by the circular cut out. Push the Feet into the holes in the Lower Base and secure with adhesive, if required. Slide the Push Button through the front hole in the Lower Base, and leave slightly protruding as shown in the images above. Snap the left and right Holly Leaves into their respective holes. Step 4: Electronics Place the Battery into the battery housing on the right hand side of the Lower Base. Guide the Battery cable around to the central Power/Input housing and connect the cable to the Power module. Connect the Power module to the Input Button and place into position as shown below. Connect one of the Wire modules onto the end of the Button. Guide the Wire module around to the Fork housing. Fit the Fork Module into this housing and connect the Wire module to the single end. Connect both fans either end of the Fork module's output, and connect another Wire module to the last remaining output in the centre of the Fork (shown below). Connect the output end of this Wire module to the RBG LED, and mount this onto the block positioned to the left of the Fork module housing, also shown below. Place the Fans onto the fan locators and switch on the Power module. You're almost done, all that's left is... Step 5: The finishing touches... Mount the Upper Base onto the Lower Base, ensuring that there aren't any cables in the way. Check that the RGB LED is exposed through the slot in the Upper Base. Place the House into the cutout in the Upper Base. Cover the Lake with a few polystyrene balls and mount the Glass Bowl onto the Upper Base. You're done! Now have fun :)

title: Star Wars X-wing: AT-AT conversion kit

description.text:
I wish FFG would make ground vehicles for the X-wing game, but so far they have not. This set of files will allow you to add AT-ATs to your game. I will leave the rules up to you, but for casual/scenario games they are quite fun. First is an X-Wing style base. It is the same dimensions as the FFG 'small' fighter base but it is double length to accommodate the longer model. There is a front to the base, indicated by the 90 degree lines which denotes the firing arc. I just lay the unit number on the base between the front and back legs. Second you'll need an AT-AT model. I used this excellent one by Kolo33:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:215574
I did not create the AT-AT model but I made five of them and they turned out well.
I used the fully assembled model, not the individual pieces, for my prints. Print the Kolo33 model at 40.5% scale. Wookiepedia tells me an X-wing is 12.5 meters long and an AT-AT is 22.5 meters tall. If the toy X-wing is 1.8" long then the AT-AT would need to be 3.25" tall. 40.5% will get you there. Third, you might need to replace the cheek guns on the sides of the head. While I was cleaning off the supports most of them broke them off. This is not the model's fault, it was never intended to be printed this small. So, I included files for replacement cheek guns should you need them. The separate cheek guns Kolo33 included were too delicate to use; again, not the model's fault.
Also, I cut the heads off of each model. Two reasons: I wanted to re-position them a little bit so every model was different, and, I wanted a very clean print for the head with no support residue. If you print the head separately you can do it without supports. Kolo33 was nice enough to provide a full model and also the model as separate pieces, making this possible. Finally, I included a 3.25" tall cylinder should you decide to use a model other than Kolo33's. First, place the cylinder on the virtual build plate of your printing software. Then drop the AT-AT model on the build plate. Keep adjusting the scale of the AT-AT until the top of the cylinder is at the top of the AT-AT's back. Finally, delete the cylinder and print. This way you know your AT-AT will be 3.5" tall; the correct scale for games of X-wing.

This file is a free download. Since it is listed as 'creative commons - attribution' there are very few restrictions on how you use these files. You are welcome (and encouraged) to print them out for yourself for personal use. You are also allowed to buy and sell physical copies of the models. However, if you use my files and my pictures you should provide a link back to where you got them. Please note that these permissions only apply the files that I have posted. Kolo33 has his files (last I checked) listed as "non-commercial" so please respect his request. Thanks.

comments.text:
Well, I’ve seen a properly tuned [level plate level, clean nozzle, decent filament, etc.] $400 printer make little AT-AT-s like mine.
I think it has as much to do with the 3D file as it does the printer. Take the cheek guns on the Kolo AT-AT model for example. If I had printed them full scale I'm sure they would turn out just fine. When I shrunk them down to the size I wanted, my printer just couldn’t handle it. When I design my own parts to 3D print I avoid making any feature wider than 0.040”. The nozzle on my extruder just can’t print a “skinnier” piece of plastic than that.
The other AT-STs I’ve found on thingiverse were a similar situation. They simply had too much detail on them for printing in a greatly reduced size. The railing around the top hatch is a good example - it made a mess. The AT-ST model that I made would look terrible if somebody printed it out 12” tall; there just isn’t enough detail put into it for that size print. Printed in the right context they turn out fine.

comments.text:
Hi, i work in the blind and vision impaired sector, and have been developing some similar projects. i have looked at your design and do believe that with some modifications to the components used to build it, that you can infact reduse the size of it considerably. however i do not find it entirely necessary. i have done some work with sensory devices that included haptic and auditory feedback, that fit into a light weight case roughly the size of a smart watch. however when we are teaching mobility services to the vision impaired, one of the first things we teach is to have the nuckls flat and fingers and wrists pointing dow, so as not to bump into anything and cause unessecary injury to the hands and fingers. this technique is called bumpers down. if ytour device was to be used in the way that you have prescribed, it would allow for finger injury, or the sensors would be obstructed by the hands and fingers, where the proper safety techniques followed. i do not mean to souynd negative i love the device and i believe that it has many aplications.
i do not think that it should be used to replace traditional mobility aids (cane and guide dog) because they serve more purposes than just identifying obstacles, but i do think this would work very well as an addition to these services. if the device was adjusted to be fitted to a cane or a harness, then i think it could serve several great purposes in orientation mobility, particularly in teaching safe practice in vision impaired children. if you are interested i would love to discuss this further and with your permission, run some design tests and simulations.
